                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d145">
                <head>No. 20.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Earl <persName type="from">Granville</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Lowell</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Foreign Office</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1882-02-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 2, 1882</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to my letter of the 30th December
                    last, I have been informed by Her Majesty’s secretary of state for the home
                    department that he did not fail to <pb facs="0321" n="249" xml:id="pg_249"/>
                    refer to the lord lieutenant of Ireland your communication on the subject of
                    Denis Hayes O’Connor, now in custody under the protection of person and property
                    (Ireland) act, 1881, but that his excellency has expressed his regret that he
                    cannot, consistently with his duty, order the prisoner’s release at present.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>GRANVILLE.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
